Even were positive evidence wanting, the language of the Highlands, called Ersess which is only another form of Erysehek‚ or Irish, would indicate the origin of the people who spoke it, and point to Irelaud as the ancient home of the Scotch. From this mother country issued St. Columba, and almost 311 the early saints of the Scottish calendar. Coming from Ireland, yet frequently revisiting it, they maintained their old relation: so that their memory was equally cherished in either country, and a common day appropriated to the festi- val of each. One of these Irishmen‚ in particular, was styled a Fer-cla-leitlze¹‚ or ‘ Man of two portions,' from his divided service.
